The only production for the start symbol is  
S → NT4 NT0,  
so the first token of any string derived from S must come from NT4 and the second token must come from NT0.

In Chomsky normal form every non-terminal either produces exactly one terminal or exactly two non-terminals.  
Therefore, for S to yield a two-token string, NT4 and NT0 each have to produce a single terminal.

• Terminals producible by NT4 (via rules of the form NT4 → 'token') are:  
  t28, t6, t37, t19, t30, t41, t38, t18, t42, t27.  
  The token t10 is not among them.

Since NT4 cannot generate t10 as a single token, the string beginning with t10 cannot be produced by the grammar, regardless of what NT0 can produce.

Hence the grammar does not generate the string “t10 t41”.
